{{Infobox religious biography |background = #FFD068 | color = black |name = Gempō Yamamoto |image = Gempo Yamamoto, (5-4-23) LOC npcc.08416.jpg |caption = Gempō Yamamoto in 1923 |birth name = |alias = |dharma name = |birth_date = 1866 |birth_place = [[Japan]] |death_date = 1961 |death_place = |nationality = [[Japanese people|Japanese]] |religion = [[Zen Buddhism]] |school = [[Rinzai]] |lineage = |title = [[Rōshi|Roshi]] |location = |education = |occupation = |teacher = |reincarnation of = |predecessor = |successor = Nakagawa Soen, Nakajima Genjo |students = |spouse = |partner = |children = |website = }} {{nihongo|'''Gempō Yamamoto'''|山本玄峰|Yamamoto Genpō|1866-1961}} was the [[abbot]] of both [[Ryūtaku-ji]] and Shoin-ji in [[Japan]]—also serving temporarily as the head of the [[Myōshin-ji]] branch of [[Rinzai]] [[Zen Buddhism]].<ref name="victoria">Victoria, 3</ref>
== Biography == A renowned [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[calligrapher]], Yamamoto was a [[Rinzai]] [[Zen]] [[Buddhist]] priest who followed in the footsteps of the famous Master [[Hakuin Ekaku]]. According to the book ''Zen and the Art of Calligraphy'', Yamamoto is sometimes called the "''twentieth century [[Hakuin]]''."<ref name="terayama">Terayama, et al.; 113</ref> Like so many prolific Zen masters throughout the ages, Yamamoto had no formal education. By today's standards Gempō would be deemed [[legally blind]], and it was not until later in life that he was able to write and read. At the age of 25 he became ordained as a [[monk]], travelling during this period to various temples throughout Japan. Yamamoto is probably most remembered for his many [[zenga]] paintings, which can be found hanging at Ryūtaku-ji today.
He also produced a number of [[Inuyama ware]].<ref>http://chiyodagarou.eshizuoka.jp/e1544239.html</ref><ref>http://hakkutudou.com/shop/detail/8/stock/detail/7009</ref>
